Low protein levels in the body can have several side effects beyond the impact on nail health. Here are some potential side effects: 1. Muscle weakness: Proteins are essential for maintaining muscle strength and function. Insufficient protein intake or low protein levels in the body can lead to muscle weakness, decreased muscle mass, and poor muscle recovery. 2. Fatigue and low energy levels: Protein is a source of energy for the body. Inadequate protein intake can result in reduced energy levels and increased feelings of fatigue. 3. Slow wound healing: Proteins play a crucial role in the healing process as they are involved in tissue repair. Low protein levels can slow down wound healing and prolong the recovery process. 4. Weakened immune system: Proteins are necessary for the production of antibodies and other immune system components. Inadequate protein intake can weaken the immune system's ability to fight off infections and diseases. 5. Swelling or edema: Protein helps maintain fluid balance in the body. Insufficient protein levels can lead to fluid accumulation in tissues, resulting in swelling or edema, especially in the ankles, feet, and legs. 6. Hair and skin problems: Protein is essential for healthy hair and skin. Low protein levels can cause hair loss, thinning, and dullness, as well as dry and flaky skin. 7. Impaired cognitive function: Proteins are involved in the production of neurotransmitters and play a role in brain function. Insufficient protein intake can negatively affect cognitive function, leading to difficulties with focus, memory, and overall mental clarity. #protein #proteindeficiency #lowprotein #proteinshake #nutrition #nutritiondeficient #deficiency #brittlenails #dryskin #flakyskin #brittlehair #dullness #dullskinsolution #food #healthy #health #healthhack #healthtips #musclepain #musclemass #fitness #fit #gym #workout #for #foryou #foryourpage #foryoupage #fyp

Biotin is needed to form healthy cells in the mouth and the tongue. Nutritional deficiency in biotin results in cracking of the mouth corners since the body cannot produce sufficient fatty acids to supply the squamous or outermost layer of the lips or mouth. These fatty acids are needed to form healthy cells in the tongue and mouth. Biotin deficiencies are rare. But because people with a deficiency often show symptoms of hair loss or a scaly red rash, some doctors and supplement companies recommend increasing your intake. Most people get the biotin they need from eating a healthy diet, but there have been many claims that getting more biotin can regulate blood sugar, promote healthy hair, skin, and nails, and help pregnant moms have healthier babies. Between 30 and 100 micrograms (mcg) per day of biotin is often recommended for adolescents and adults. Biotin can also be found in some foods, including: egg yolk organ meats (liver, kidney) nuts, like almonds, peanuts, pecans, and walnuts nut butter soybeans and other legumes whole grains and cereals cauliflower bananas mushrooms To correct the nutrient deficiency, individuals can have biotin supplementation. Gluten sensitivity, also known as non-celiac gluten sensitivity or gluten intolerance, can manifest with a variety of symptoms. Common symptoms include gastrointestinal issues such as abdominal pain, bloating, and diarrhea. Additionally, individuals may experience skin-related symptoms like an itchy, burning rash with small grouped blisters or bumps, predominantly appearing on both sides of the body, especially on the elbows, knees, ear, and the neck. What is it that Causes Your Eye to Twitch? #myokymia  Myokymia is a neuromuscular condition characterized by involuntary and spontaneous muscle twitching or quivering, typically in small, localized areas of the body. These twitches are often described as rippling or worm-like movements and can occur in muscles around the eyes, face, limbs, or other parts of the body. The exact cause of myokymia is not fully understood, but it is believed to be related to abnormalities in the nerve cells that control muscle contraction. Factors such as stress, fatigue, caffeine, excessive use of digital screens, and electrolyte imbalances may contribute to the occurrence or exacerbation of myokymia. While myokymia is generally harmless and self-limiting, it can be bothersome and concerning to those experiencing it. In most cases, the twitches resolve spontaneously without any specific treatment. However, managing stress levels, getting adequate rest, and avoiding triggers such as excessive caffeine intake or eye strain may help reduce the frequency or intensity of myokymic episodes. If myokymia becomes persistent, widespread, or is accompanied by other symptoms, it is advisable to seek medical attention. Rarely, myokymia can be a sign of an underlying neurological disorder or nerve dysfunction that requires further evaluation and treatment. Understanding myokymia as a benign condition can provide reassurance to individuals experiencing these muscle twitches, but it's always important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and guidance. #Myokymia #MuscleTwitching #NeuromuscularCondition #InvoluntaryMovements #SpontaneousTwitches #MuscleQuivering #NeurologicalDisorder #NerveDysfunction #StressManagement #Fatigue #CaffeineSensitivity #DigitalEyeStrain #ElectrolyteImbalance #SelfLimitingCondition #Neurology #MuscleSpasms #BenignMuscleTwitches #HealthAwareness #MedicalAttention #SeekAdvice #doctor #medicine #healthcare #interesting #interestingfacts #interestingvideos #interestingthings #healthcare #eyetwitch #eyetwitching

High eosinophil levels can lead to various skin and body complications. For the skin, it can worsen symptoms of eczema, causing intense itching, redness, and dry patches. It can also lead to chronic urticaria, resulting in recurring episodes of itchy hives. In terms of the body, elevated eosinophil levels can exacerbate symptoms of asthma, such as wheezing and shortness of breath. Additionally, it can contribute to allergic rhinitis & complications of it, leading to sneezing, congestion, and itchy eyes. For someone who has been told from childhood not to smell their food so up close this was foreign for me. But i am determined to do what i can to support my sense of smell so here we are Please this is NOT MEDICAL ADVICE. I am NOT a medical doctor. The only science training I have is in immunology and epidemiology, which is not medicine.  When we get sick, some of our symptoms are actually a result of our immune response against the virus. The fever, the headache, and the stuffy nose are all based on the inflammatory response from the immune system trying to attack the disease-causing agent. Depending on what you are sick with, the recovery is different. Although I am feeling well, my body is still rebuilding the pieces from my COVID infection, which includes repairing my olfactory epithelium, which is a group of cells that support the olfactory nerve, which is crucial in sensing smell. Because of this loss, I cannot acutely taste all the flavours in my food beyond the sweet, salty, bitter and sour profiles my tastebuds pick up. In all, it is not an ideal situation for someone who creates and shares recipes for a living.  Olfactory retraining has been recommended to help support recovering smells and retrain the olfactory system to get smelling again. It involves smelling a few strong and diverse scents for 20-25sec a few times a day (rose, lemon, eucalyptus and cloves are usually recommended) as well as scents of sentimental value.  In addition, I just try and stay healthy.
